# Spec 0022 — Declarative optical-system constructor (computation expression)

## 0. Binding constraints

This spec adds a declarative F# constructor for the existing
`BaseOpticalSystem` value (`Berreman/Berreman/Media.fs:63`) so that
experiments under `Berreman/Analytics/Examples/` stop hand-building
deep record literals. All work lands in the F# core library
(`Berreman/Berreman/`), one example script under
`Berreman/Analytics/Examples/`, and the existing test project
(`Berreman/BerremanTests/`).

The constructor MUST produce values structurally equal (F#
structural equality `=`) to today's hand-built records, so the
existing pipeline consumes them unchanged. The solver core
(`Berreman/Berreman/BerremanMatrix.fs`) and the solver entry
point — the `OpticalSystemSolver` type
(`Berreman/Berreman/Solvers.fs:199`, constructor
`OpticalSystemSolver (info : IncidentLightInfo, system :
OpticalSystem, parameters : SolverParameters)`) — MUST NOT be
modified by this spec.

This spec supersedes the prior "wedge depolarization" placeholder
that occupied `0022`. Wedge depolarization is NOT in scope here.

> Authoring note: an earlier draft of this spec (see the prior
> `.history` rows) cited several wrong pointers produced by an
> unstable tool environment (e.g. `OpticalSystem` at line 303, a
> `Solvers.solve` function, a `Berreman/Tests/` project). This
> revision re-grounds every pointer against the live tree.

## 1. Problem statement

Examples under `Berreman/Analytics/Examples/` assemble their
optical systems by hand as nested record literals.
`MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:33` is representative: `let filmSystem = {
description = Some "Multilayer thin film system."; upper =
OpticalProperties.vacuum; films = [ ... ]; lower =
OpticalProperties.vacuum }` (the record spans
`MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:35`–`81`), which it then lifts and makes
dispersive via `.fullSystem.dispersive` (`MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:84`).
The outer `{ description; upper; films; lower }` wrapper plus the
`films` list is deep, easy to mis-order, and recopied per
experiment.

The relevant core types already exist in
`Berreman/Berreman/Media.fs`:

- `BaseOpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:63`) = `{ description : string
  option; upper : OpticalProperties; films : List<Layer>; lower :
  OpticalProperties }`, the four-field "incident / films / exit"
  shape this constructor targets. It exposes `member this.fullSystem`
  (`Media.fs:71`) which lifts it to a full `OpticalSystem`.
- `OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`, declared `and OpticalSystem =`) =
  `{ description; upper; films; substrate : Substrate option; lower }`
  — produced from a `BaseOpticalSystem` via `.fullSystem`; this
  spec does NOT build `OpticalSystem` directly.
- `Layer` is the element type of `films : List<Layer>`
  (`Media.fs`, type `Layer`); the example `films` lists at
  `MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:37` show how a `Layer` is constructed.

The goal is a thin, declarative surface that emits exactly the
`BaseOpticalSystem` record above — no new solver behaviour, no new
optical model.

## 2. Constructor surface — the `baseOpticalSystem` computation expression

The implementation MUST provide a single F# **computation
expression** named `baseOpticalSystem`. A fluent builder MUST NOT
be added in addition; pick the computation expression and only
that.

The CE MUST support exactly these custom operations, and no
others:

- `description (d : string)` — sets `description = Some d`.
- `incident (p : OpticalProperties)` — sets `upper = p` (the
  incident medium).
- `exit (p : OpticalProperties)` — sets `lower = p` (the exit /
  transmitted medium).
- `layer (l : Layer)` — appends one pre-built `Layer` to `films`.
  This operation MUST be repeatable, and the resulting `films`
  list MUST preserve the order the `layer` operations appear in
  the expression (first `layer` = `films` head). The CE MUST NOT
  introduce a new `Layer` constructor; callers build each `Layer`
  exactly as the existing `films` lists do (reference:
  `MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:37`).

Default state when an operation is omitted:

- `description` defaults to `None`.
- `upper` and `lower` default to `OpticalProperties.vacuum` (the
  value `MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:36` and `MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:81`
  use).
- `films` defaults to `[]`.

The expression MUST evaluate to a `BaseOpticalSystem`
(`Media.fs:63`). For any inputs, `baseOpticalSystem { incident u;
layer l; exit x }` MUST equal `{ description = None; upper = u;
films = [ l ]; lower = x }` under F# `=`.

Implementation MUST use conventional F# CE machinery —
`[<CustomOperation>]`-attributed builder members plus
`Yield`/`Zero` to seed the default state. It MUST NOT use
reflection, quotations, or runtime code generation.

## 3. Placement and project wiring

Add the constructor as a NEW file
`Berreman/Berreman/OpticalSystemBuilder.fs`, in the same namespace
as `Berreman/Berreman/Media.fs`, exposing an `[<AutoOpen>]` module
that makes the types in `Media.fs` visible and binds the
`baseOpticalSystem` builder value. Placing it in the core library
(next to the types it builds) keeps every consumer — Analytics,
Examples, Tests — able to reach it.

Register the file in `Berreman/Berreman/Berreman.fsproj`
immediately after the `Media.fs` entry (`Berreman.fsproj:45`;
current order around it is `Media.fs` (45) → `BerremanMatrix.fs`
(46) → `Solvers.fs` (47)). The new `<Compile
Include="OpticalSystemBuilder.fs" />` MUST sit after `Media.fs`
(it depends on `BaseOpticalSystem`/`Layer`) and before
`BerremanMatrix.fs`.

## 4. Reuse — build on existing primitives

The CE is a constructor only; it MUST reach for what already
exists rather than inventing parallels:

- `BaseOpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:63`) — the exact output record;
  do not define a new system record.
- `BaseOpticalSystem.fullSystem` (`Media.fs:71`) — the existing
  lift to `OpticalSystem`; callers that need a full system or a
  dispersive one continue to chain `.fullSystem` / `.dispersive`
  as today (`MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:84`). The CE itself does NOT
  add lifting or dispersion operations.
- `OpticalProperties.vacuum` (used at `MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:36`)
  — the value callers pass to `incident` / `exit`. The CE MUST NOT
  introduce new `OpticalProperties` constructors; it consumes
  whatever `OpticalProperties` value the caller supplies.

## 5. Example migration (proof)

Migrate exactly one example to prove the constructor against a real
hand-built literal:

- `Berreman/Analytics/Examples/MultilayerThinFilm.fsx` — replace
  the `let filmSystem = { ... }` record literal
  (`MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:33`, body `:35`–`81`) with
  `let filmSystem = baseOpticalSystem { ... }`. The downstream
  `.fullSystem.dispersive` usage (`MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:84`)
  MUST remain unchanged.

The migrated `filmSystem` MUST be structurally equal to its
pre-migration value. The dispersive `Glass.fsx` /
`Glass_Dispersive.fsx` builders (which assemble a different,
`*WithDisp` record shape at `Glass.fsx:80` and
`Glass_Dispersive.fsx:106`) are NOT migrated here; extending the
constructor to the dispersive variant is a follow-up cycle. No
other `Examples/*.fsx` script is modified.

## 6. Tests

Add a NEW test file `Berreman/BerremanTests/ConstructorTests.fs`
and register it in `Berreman/BerremanTests/BerremanTests.fsproj`'s
`Compile` list. Use the same test framework the sibling tests in
that project use — read `Berreman/BerremanTests/SolverTests.fs`
for the framework and module conventions, and follow them.

The tests MUST assert structural equality (`=`) between
CE-constructed `BaseOpticalSystem` values and the equivalent
hand-built records for: a single-layer system, a multi-layer
system (order-preserving), and the default/empty case.

## 7. Out of scope — do not expand

To bound the change against plausible additive hallucination:

- No change to `Berreman/Berreman/BerremanMatrix.fs` or to the
  `OpticalSystemSolver` type (`Berreman/Berreman/Solvers.fs:199`).
- No constructor for `OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`) or
  `ShortOpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:56`); this slice builds only
  `BaseOpticalSystem`. Lifting stays with the existing
  `.fullSystem` member.
- No refactor of `Berreman/Analytics/StandardSystems.fs`;
  re-expressing its helpers via the new CE is a follow-up.
- No second construction surface (no fluent builder alongside the
  CE), no dispersive-variant builder, no caching, no
  validation/erroring framework, no configuration knobs, no
  versioning, and no backwards-compatibility shims. The CE is a
  pure constructor.
- No new `OpticalProperties`, `Layer`, `Thickness`, `Substrate`,
  or material / dispersion constructors.
- No wedge / depolarization modelling (the superseded placeholder
  subject).

## Acceptance criteria

- AC-A1: `baseOpticalSystem { incident u; layer l; exit x }`
  returns a value equal under F# `=` to `{ description = None;
  upper = u; films = [ l ]; lower = x }` (`Media.fs:63`).
- AC-A2: Multiple `layer` operations preserve order —
  `baseOpticalSystem { layer l1; layer l2 }` yields `films =
  [ l1; l2 ]`.
- AC-A3: With no `incident`/`exit`/`layer`/`description` supplied,
  the CE yields `description = None`, `upper = OpticalProperties.vacuum`,
  `lower = OpticalProperties.vacuum`, `films = []`.
- AC-A4: After migration, `MultilayerThinFilm.fsx`'s `filmSystem`
  is structurally equal to its pre-migration value, and
  `.fullSystem.dispersive` (`MultilayerThinFilm.fsx:84`) still
  type-checks and runs unchanged.
- AC-A5: `Berreman/Berreman/BerremanMatrix.fs` and the
  `OpticalSystemSolver` type (`Berreman/Berreman/Solvers.fs:199`)
  are unchanged by this spec; a system built via the CE and lifted
  with `.fullSystem` solves identically to the hand-built
  equivalent.
- AC-A6: `Berreman/BerremanTests/ConstructorTests.fs` exists, is
  registered in `BerremanTests.fsproj`, contains tests covering
  AC-A1 through AC-A3, and they pass under the `unit-tests` gate.
- AC-A7: The solution builds (the `build` gate) with
  `OpticalSystemBuilder.fs` registered in `Berreman.fsproj` after
  `Media.fs`, and no `Examples/*.fsx` other than
  `MultilayerThinFilm.fsx` is modified.

## Files in scope

- `Berreman/Berreman/OpticalSystemBuilder.fs` (new) — the
  `baseOpticalSystem` computation expression.
- `Berreman/Berreman/Berreman.fsproj` (edit) — register the new
  file after `Media.fs`.
- `Berreman/Analytics/Examples/MultilayerThinFilm.fsx` (edit) —
  migrate the `filmSystem` literal to the CE.
- `Berreman/BerremanTests/ConstructorTests.fs` (new) — equality
  tests.
- `Berreman/BerremanTests/BerremanTests.fsproj` (edit) — register
  the new test file.

## Test artifacts

- `Berreman/BerremanTests/ConstructorTests.fs` — tests (using the
  framework of `Berreman/BerremanTests/SolverTests.fs`) asserting
  structural equality between CE-built and hand-built
  `BaseOpticalSystem` values for the single-layer, multi-layer
  (ordered), and default cases. The `unit-tests` gate runs the
  `BerremanTests` project.

